Marcus CrowView Marcus Crow’s profile • 3rd+ Co-founder: 10,000 HOURS. :: Skill acquisition for professional expertise. :: A scholar practitioner for 20+ years.

1w
Bladders can last 90-100 mins. The further down Maslow's triangle you get, the more you lose the group. And you will lose. So, rather than have one or two people walking in and out of the room to the bathroom for an hour or so. Have a break and get it all done at once.

And when the client says "we've got lots to cover, so we want a working lunch", advise them against it. It's a bad idea. Even a 20-minute break to get and eat a sandwich / sushi roll, return a call, see the outside sky is fruitful.

Catherine SimpsonView Catherine Simpson’s profile (She/Her) • 3rd+ Domain Principal Collaboration - Facilitation and Solution Design

3d
Check with participants for more than dietary requirements before events - sensory, sight, hearing, mobility requirements should all impact your design.
Check and check again if all participants will be in the room or if it is a hybrid event (some virtual some in person) or if the event is totally virtual. The design for each is different.
Be conscious of the environment you are in, temperature, sound, smell all impact. If possible manipulate them to your expectations if not manipulate your design to mitigate any adverse impact.
Expect things to change
Don't be afraid of conflict, embrace and use it.

Traca SavadogoView Traca Savadogo’s profile • 3rd+ Keynote Speaker | Market and Relationship Strategist | Mastermind Founder | TEDx Speaker | Author

Lauren Sowers can you give an example of one you like to use?

Lauren SowersView Lauren Sowers’ profile • 3rd+ I'm a multi-dimensional communications partner, optimizing your conflict and crisis situations through a unique investigative lens. I provide coaching, mediation, and facilitation services.

1w
Traca Savadogo absolutely! I usually try to keep it on theme for the group. The quick and easy one is to pair people off and have them introduce their partner, just so we all find our voices in the room at the start. A more fun version for a group where folks know one another is a prompt to write something down about themselves (specific and tied to the purpose, like “your first job”) and turn it into a paper airplane. Let people pick up a plane, read it aloud, and guess whose plane they found.

For groups that I work with more regularly, it can involve a tiny ask for prep. An easy one is to bring something small that represents your connection to xyz (your work, this project, etc.) and speak to why. For instance, I usually bring matches. People bring the funniest stuff.
Would love to hear more if ya’ll have any!

Rachna VermaView Rachna Verma’s profile • 3rd+ Strategy & Transformation Lead

1w
Align on roles & responsibilities. Who is on the timer? Who is going to group the post it’s, who is going to watch questions/comments from the virtual audience?

Know the layout of the room and ensure it’s conducive to the session you are running. NB, theatre style not great for collaboration

Arrive early if onsite, set up the space and familiarise with amenities etc

Lastly, think about how you show up as facilitator, what type of energy do you want to bring? What can you do to set yourself up for a good session? Gym, run etc. good music to get the energy flowing

Accept: that there’s always something will not go according to plan

Simon BanksView Simon Banks’ profile • 2nd Author & Keynote Speaker on Creativity, Innovation & Design | Design Thinking | EmCee | Recovering Artist | Visual Storyteller | Occupational Philosophers Podcast Host

6d
Breaks mean having a break - let people chat about stuff not to do with the workshop, mingle, laugh etc.
10 minutes never work nor does 15 - everyone is always back late.
Go 20 mins as a minimum.

Let lunch be 45 min at least and really workshop how they get that food. Do you want one line for food for 200 people (see it all the time!)

Keep mentos off the tables until much later in the day otherwise, for some reason, people eat waaaay too many and then crash. Time the sugar rush until late in the day (if at all) and send them sky high to finish the day 😁

Marcus CrowView Marcus Crow’s profile • 3rd+ Co-founder: 10,000 HOURS. :: Skill acquisition for professional expertise. :: A scholar practitioner for 20+ years.

1w
Bladders can last 90-100 mins. The further down Maslow's triangle you get, the more you lose the group. And you will lose. So, rather than have one or two people walking in and out of the room to the bathroom for an hour or so. Have a break and get it all done at once.

And when the client says "we've got lots to cover, so we want a working lunch", advise them against it. It's a bad idea. Even a 20-minute break to get and eat a sandwich / sushi roll, return a call, see the outside sky is fruitful.

Catherine SimpsonView Catherine Simpson’s profile (She/Her) • 3rd+ Domain Principal Collaboration - Facilitation and Solution Design

3d
Check with participants for more than dietary requirements before events - sensory, sight, hearing, mobility requirements should all impact your design.
Check and check again if all participants will be in the room or if it is a hybrid event (some virtual some in person) or if the event is totally virtual. The design for each is different.
Be conscious of the environment you are in, temperature, sound, smell all impact. If possible manipulate them to your expectations if not manipulate your design to mitigate any adverse impact.
Expect things to change
Don't be afraid of conflict, embrace and use it.

Traca SavadogoView Traca Savadogo’s profile • 3rd+ Keynote Speaker | Market and Relationship Strategist | Mastermind Founder | TEDx Speaker | Author

1w
Lauren Sowers can you give an example of one you like to use?

Lauren SowersView Lauren Sowers’ profile • 3rd+ I'm a multi-dimensional communications partner, optimizing your conflict and crisis situations through a unique investigative lens. I provide coaching, mediation, and facilitation services.

1w
Traca Savadogo absolutely! I usually try to keep it on theme for the group. The quick and easy one is to pair people off and have them introduce their partner, just so we all find our voices in the room at the start. A more fun version for a group where folks know one another is a prompt to write something down about themselves (specific and tied to the purpose, like “your first job”) and turn it into a paper airplane. Let people pick up a plane, read it aloud, and guess whose plane they found.

For groups that I work with more regularly, it can involve a tiny ask for prep. An easy one is to bring something small that represents your connection to xyz (your work, this project, etc.) and speak to why. For instance, I usually bring matches. People bring the funniest stuff.
Would love to hear more if ya’ll have any!

Rachna VermaView Rachna Verma’s profile • 3rd+ Strategy & Transformation Lead

1w
Align on roles & responsibilities. Who is on the timer? Who is going to group the post it’s, who is going to watch questions/comments from the virtual audience?

Know the layout of the room and ensure it’s conducive to the session you are running. NB, theatre style not great for collaboration

Arrive early if onsite, set up the space and familiarise with amenities etc

Lastly, think about how you show up as facilitator, what type of energy do you want to bring? What can you do to set yourself up for a good session? Gym, run etc. good music to get the energy flowing

Accept-Anticipate-Prepare (Tried to make the third one an A as well. Act maybe? 😆)

Accept: that there’s always something will not go according to plan
Anticipate: what these could be
Prepare: a mitigation plan

Could be something as trivial as not being allowed to put up flip charts on the walls, or 4 participants showing when you’re expecting 24

Simon BanksView Simon Banks’ profile • 2nd Author & Keynote Speaker on Creativity, Innovation & Design | Design Thinking | EmCee | Recovering Artist | Visual Storyteller | Occupational Philosophers Podcast Host

6d
Breaks mean having a break - let people chat about stuff not to do with the workshop, mingle, laugh etc.
10 minutes never work nor does 15 - everyone is always back late.
Go 20 mins as a minimum.

Let lunch be 45 min at least and really workshop how they get that food. Do you want one line for food for 200 people (see it all the time!)

Keep mentos off the tables until much later in the day otherwise, for some reason, people eat waaaay too many and then crash. Time the sugar rush until late in the day (if at all) and send them sky high to finish the day 😁
